- (i1 @ (i2 + i3.T)) - (i4 @ i5) + i6.T

Each of these is another unique way.

I can also consider more complex groupings, such as nested operations:

- (i1 @ i2) @ (i3 - i4)
- (i1 + (i2 @ (i3 - i4))) @ (i5 + i6)
- ((i1 @ i2) + (i3 @ i4)) - (i5 @ i6)
- (i1 @ (i2 @ (i3 - i4))) + (i5 @ i6)
- (i1 + (i2 @ (i3 - i4 @ i5))) @ i6

Each of these is a different way of nesting the operations.

I can also vary the order of operations, such as subtraction before addition or multiplication:

- (i1 - i2) + (i3 @ i4)
- (i1 @ i2) - (i3 @ i4)
- (i1 + i2) @ (i3 - i4)
- (i1 @ (i2 - i3)) + (i4 @ i5)
- (i1 + (i2 @ i3)) - (i4 @ i5)
- (i1 @ i2 + i3) - (i4 @ i5) + i6

Another idea is to use the transpose in different places, like applying it to different variables or in combination with other operations.

For example:

- (i1.T @ i2) + (i3 - i4)
